  "text": "This approach has apparently only advantages compared to that of [CITATION_1] . It is easy to encode and use even by non-expert users. It is more flexible, i.e. straightforward to modify for example to 1) handle continuous-time systems 2) change the objective into H 2 minimization or multiobjectives 3) take into account complex requirements such as a structure of the solution. The inflation of size of the system -but not necessarily of the filter-will have a smaller impact on the computational time than techniques using LMIs, since the only variables are those of the filter to be designed (no additional variables needed, like Lyapunov matrices). Also the technique often leads to locally optimal solutions, where 'often' depends on the objective to be minimized, whereas this should be seldom the case with most ILMIs (see [CITATION_2] and references therein, in particular [CITATION_3] ). Finally since it is generally fast for moderate size problems, it can be run multiple times from several feasible initial solutions. And so by getting several times the same best solution one gets an increasing probability that this solution is indeed locally optimal or even globally optimal.",
